(89, 'ODIN overall social data score', 'bar graph', 1, 0, 'Statistical production processes', 'Production', 'Skills & Knowledge', 'Organization', 1, '', 'Open Data Watch (http://odin.opendatawatch.com/)', 'ODIN score on social statistics. Social Statistics include:\n1. Population and Vital Statistics\n2. Education Facilities\n3. Education Outcomes\n4. Health Facilities\n5. Health Outcomes\n6. Reproductive Health\n7. Gender Statistics\n8. Crime and Justice Statistics\n9. Poverty Statistics ', 'index (0 to 100)', 1, ''),
(90, 'Online data accessibility ', 'binary', 1, 0, 'Accountability', 'Dissemination', 'Skills & Knowledge', 'System', 1, '', 'PARIS21 ', 'The accessibility of online data. ', 'indicator (0 or 1)', 0, ''),
(91, 'Open Government', 'binary', 1, 0, 'Accountability', 'Dissemination', 'Politics and Power', 'System', 1, 'different values in metabase vs. prioritization tool', 'OGP (https://www.opengovpartnership.org/participants)', 'Whether the country participates in the Open Government Partnership', 'indicator (0 or 1)', 1, ''),
(92, 'Per capita GDP growth', 'ordinal', 1, 0, 'Existing data', 'Production', 'Skills & Knowledge', 'System', 1, '', 'World Bank Statistical Capacity Indicator', 'Existence of data on per capita GDP growth, according to international standards. GDP per capita is the sum of gross value added by all resident producers in the economy plus any product taxes (less subsidies) not included in the valuation of output, divided by mid-year population. Growth is calculated from constant price GDP data in local currency. Sustained economic growth increases average incomes and is strongly linked to poverty reduction. GDP per capita provides a basic measure of the value of output per person, which is an indirect indicator of per capita income. Growth in GDP and GDP per capita are considered broad measures of economic growth.', 'indicator (0 to 1)', 1, ''),
(93, 'Periodicity and timeliness assessment of statistical capacity (scale 0 - 100)', 'bar graph', 1, 0, 'Quality assurance and codes of conduct', 'Production', 'Skills & Knowledge', 'Organization', 1, '', 'World Bank Statistical Capacity Indicator', 'Quality of statistical production periodicity (composite of indicators).', 'index (0 to 100)', 1, ''),
(94, 'Population', 'bar graph', 1, 0, 'Existing data', 'Production', 'Resources', 'System', 1, 'useful for country page?', 'PARIS21 ', 'Total number of people living in the country. ', 'people', 1, ''),
(95, 'Population census', 'binary', 1, 0, 'Statistical production processes', 'Production', 'Skills & Knowledge', 'Organization', 1, '', 'World Bank Statistical Capacity Indicator', 'Existence of a population census according to international standards. Population censuses collect data on the size, distribution and composition of population and information on a broad range of social and economic characteristics of the population. It also provides sampling frames for household and other surveys. It is recommended that population censuses be conducted at least every 10 years.', 'indicator (0 or 1)', 1, ''),
(96, 'Poverty surveys', 'ordinal', 1, 0, 'Statistical production processes', 'Production', 'Skills & Knowledge', 'Organization', 1, '', 'World Bank Statistical Capacity Indicator', 'Existence of povery surveys according to international standards. Poverty surveys collect data on household income, consumption and expenditure, including income in kind. They typically include income, expenditure, and consumption surveys, household budget surveys, Integrated Surveys, Living Standard Measuring Surveys, and other poverty related surveys. It is recommended that poverty surveys be conducted at least every 3 to 5 years.', 'indicator (0 to 1)', 1, ''),
(97, 'Press releases ', 'binary', 1, 0, 'Communication', 'Dissemination', 'Skills & Knowledge', 'Organization', 0, 'redundant', 'PARIS21 ', 'The recent press release from the national statitics office. ', '', 0, ''),
(98, 'Press releases issued at least quarterly', 'binary', 1, 0, 'Communication', 'Dissemination', 'Skills & Knowledge', 'Organization', 1, 'fold into another dissemination variable?', 'PARIS21', 'Timeliness and frequency of official statements issued to journalists on statistical indicators', 'indicator (0 or 1)', 0, ''),
(99, 'Primary completion', 'ordinal', 1, 0, 'Existing data', 'Production', 'Resources', 'System', 1, '', 'World Bank Statistical Capacity Indicator', 'Existence of data on primary education completion, according to international standards. Primary completion rate (PCR) is the number of students successfully completing the last year of (or graduating from) primary school in a given year, divided by the number of children of official graduation age in the population. Because of difficulties with developing data based on this definition, data analysis is generally based on the PCR proxy indicator which is the number of children reaching the last year of primary school (as defined by a country) net of repeaters. The indicator, which monitors education system coverage and student progression, is intended to measure human capital formation and school system quality and efficiency and relates to the second MDG to achieve universal primary education.', 'indicator (0 to 1)', 1, ''),
(100, 'Processing-friendly data format', 'binary', 1, 0, 'Relationship with users', 'Dissemination', 'Politics and Power', 'System', 1, '', 'PARIS21 ', 'The data format is processing-friendly if it is published in digital formats such as .csv and .xls/.xlsx instead of formats such as .doc or .pdf. ', 'indicator (0 or 1)', 0, ''),
(101, 'National Development Plan timespan', 'ordinal', 1, 0, 'Plans', 'Planning', 'Resources', 'System', 0, '?', 'PARIS21', 'The timespan for the Poverty Reduction Strategy Paper or the national development plan. ', '', 0, ''),
(102, 'Regulatory quality ', 'bar graph', 1, 0, 'Accountability', 'Planning', 'Politics and Power', 'System', 1, '', 'World Bank Governance Indicator (http://info.worldbank.org/governance/wgi)', 'Regulatory quality captures perceptions of the ability of the government to formulate and implement sound policies and regulations that permit and promote private sector development.', 'index (-3 to 3)', 0, ''),
(103, 'Rule of law ', 'bar graph', 1, 0, 'Legislation, Principles and Institutional setting', 'Planning', 'Resources', 'System', 1, '', 'World Bank Governance Indicator (http://info.worldbank.org/governance/wgi)', 'Rule of law captures perceptions of the extent to which agents have confidence in and abide by the rules of society, and in particular the quality of contract enforcement, property rights, the police, and the courts, as well as the likelihood of crime and violence', 'index (-3 to 3)', 0, ''),
(104, 'SDDS subscription ', 'binary', 1, 1, 'Quality assurance and codes of conduct', 'Dissemination', 'Skills & Knowledge', 'Organization', 1, '', 'International Monetary Fund ', 'The SDDS is a global benchmark for disseminating macroeconomic statistics to the public. SDDS subscription indicates that a country meets the test of “good statistical citizenship.” The SDDS Guide for Subscribers and Users contains details on commitments undertaken by a subscriber, and is available on the DSBB. Countries that subscribe to the SDDS agree to follow good practices in four areas: the coverage, periodicity, and timeliness of data; public access to those data; data integrity; and data quality.\nSubscribing countries commit to:\nDisseminate the data required by the SDDS punctually and with the prescribed periodicity and timeliness on a national webpage, the National Summary Data Page (NSDP), which is hyperlinked to the DSBB. A complete list of NSDPs can be accessed by clicking here.\nProvide to the IMF an advance release calendar (ARC) containing release dates for the current month and at least the following three months for each prescribed category of data for posting on the DSBB.\nProvide detailed information about their statistical practices, or metadata, for dissemination on the DSBB. The metadata follow the rigorous format of the Data Quality Assessment Framework (DQAF). The DQAF was developed by the IMF to assess the quality of countries’ economic and financial data. Details about DQAF are available on the Data Quality Reference Site.\nCertify the accuracy of the metadata on an annual basis.\nUse standardized electronic reporting procedures to monitor more effectively their observance of the SDDS is also a required undertaking for SDDS subscribers.', 'indicator (0 or 1)', 0, '1'),
(105, 'Share of foreign support dedicated to demographic and social statistics (ten years)', 'bar graph', 1, 0, 'Funds infrastructure', 'Investment', 'Resources', 'System', 1, '', 'PARIS21 ', 'Share of foreign support dedicated to demographic and social statistics', 'percentage', 0, ''),
(106, 'Share of foreign support dedicated to economic statistics (ten years)', 'bar graph', 1, 0, 'Funds infrastructure', 'Investment', 'Resources', 'System', 1, '', 'PARIS21 ', 'Share of foreign support dedicated to economic statistics.', 'percentage', 0, ''),
